Section 1: Introduction

This project aims to analyze and forecast Bitcoin prices using Meta Prophet. Bitcoin gained significant popularity a few years ago, so let’s gather some price data and forecast it one year ahead. I have two datasets: ‘bitcoinpart’, covering 2016–2020 with approximately three data points per month, and ‘bitcoin’, covering 2015–2020 with daily data points.

Section 2: Forecasting

I will now start to run R code and forecast the bitcoin price data

2.1 Part of the Bitcoin price dataset - ‘bitcoinpart’

I have installed the Prophet package using the code install.packages("prophet"), and loaded the library using the code library(prophet)

2.2 Bitcoin price dataset

Now we will forecast and analyse the full dataset from 2015-06-13 to 2020-06-10

# load dataset

Bitcoin <- read_csv("data/BitcoinPrice.csv")

## 2185 2021-06-05 8682.178  -609.6908   17224.23

# plot

plot(model2, forecast2)

dyplot.prophet(model2, forecast2)
prophet_plot_components(model2, forecast2)

2.3 Comparison

From the forecast plots for both dataset above, we can observe that the dataset with more data points (BitcoinPrice.csv) produces a more reliable and accurate forecast, whereas the dataset with fewer data points (BitcoinPricepart.csv) results in higher uncertainty and lower precision. The full dataset shows detailed trends, leading to a lower forecasting error and a narrower confidence interval, while the limited dataset produces a smoother but less confident prediction with wider uncertainty bands. Toward the end of the forecast, the BitcoinPrice.csv model shows a dramatic increase in error. This highlights the importance of data frequency in time series forecasting, as more frequent observations improve accuracy and reduce forecast errors. Therefore, for investment or trading decisions, the full dataset is the better choice due to its higher confidence, lower error, and more precise trend detection.
